\section{Real-Time Chat Logic Implementation}

The following JavaScript code implements the core functionality of the real-time chat system using Supabase as the backend service. Important sections of the code are highlighted for better understanding.

\subsection{Key Code Snippets}

\begin{verbatim}
// Supabase Client Initialization (IMPORTANT)
const supabaseUrl = "https://your-project-url.supabase.co";
const supabaseKey = "your-anon-key";
const { createClient } = supabase;
const db = createClient(supabaseUrl, supabaseKey);


// Send Message to Database (IMPORTANT)
async function sendMessage() {
  const username = document.getElementById("username").value.trim();
  const content = document.getElementById("message").value.trim();
  if (!username || !content) return;

  await db.from("chat_messages").insert([{ username, content }]);

  document.getElementById("message").value = "";
}


// Load Messages from Database (IMPORTANT)
async function loadMessages() {
  const { data } = await db
    .from("chat_messages")
    .select("*")
    .order("created_at", { ascending: true });

  data.forEach(msg => addMessage(msg.id, msg.username, msg.content));
}


// Delete Message (IMPORTANT)
async function deleteMessage(id) {
  await db.from("chat_messages").delete().eq("id", id);
}


// Real-Time Updates using Subscription (VERY IMPORTANT)
db.channel("chat-messages-channel")
  .on(
    "postgres_changes",
    { event: "INSERT", schema: "public", table: "chat_messages" },
    (payload) => addMessage(payload.new.id, payload.new.username,
    payload.new.content)
  )
  .on(
    "postgres_changes",
    { event: "DELETE", schema: "public", table: "chat_messages" },
    (payload) => document.querySelector(`[data-id='${payload.old.id}
    ']`)?.remove()
  )
  .subscribe();
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Explanation of Key Components}

The chat system is built using Supabase to enable real-time communication between users. The Supabase client initialization is a critical step that connects the frontend application to the backend database. The \texttt{sendMessage()} function allows users to send messages, which are stored in the \texttt{chat\_messages} table. The \texttt{loadMessages()} function retrieves existing messages from the database and displays them in chronological order. The \texttt{deleteMessage()} function enables users to remove their messages from the database. The most important feature of this system is the real-time subscription mechanism, which listens for database changes such as new message insertions and deletions. This ensures that all users see updates instantly without refreshing the page, making the chat system dynamic and interactive.

